# Context

This example tests the usage of an external potential provided by the AGAMA library (https://agama.software/).
A Plummer sphere is generated and used to create a potential from a multipole expansion using AGAMA.
This potential, stored in the potential.txt file is then used inside SWIFT to evolve the Plummer sphere,
switching off its self-gravity.
The conservation of the density profile as well as the energy is used as a proxy.


This example demonstrates the use of an external potential provided by the AGAMA library (https://agama.software/).
A Plummer sphere is generated and used to construct a potential through a multipole expansion with AGAMA.
The resulting potential is stored in the `potential.txt` file and then used within SWIFT to evolve the
Plummer sphere while disabling its self-gravity.
The conservation of the density profile and total energy is used as a proxy for validating the evolution.


# How to run this example

In a terminal at the root of the "swiftsim" directory, type:

`./autogen.sh`

Then, configure swift to take into account external potentials. Type:

`./configure --with-agama=path_to_agama_directory --with-ext-potential=agama`

Feel free to adapt other configurations parameters depending on your system. Then, build the code by typing:

`make`

Finally, to run this example, open a terminal in the present directory and type:

`./run.sh`


Note that the AGAMA potential file `potiential.txt` can be created by running:

`./makePlummerPotential.py`

The initial conditions are obtained with the pNbody script:

`ic_plummer   -N 100000 --Mtot 1e-2 -a 0.1 --Rmax 20 -t swift -o plummer.hdf5`

